revision.text:
The '''7199''' is a [[vacuum tube]], combining a [[pentode]] and [[triode]].<ref name="HopkinsMoore1999">{{cite book|last1=Hopkins|first1=Gregg|last2=Moore|first2=Bill|title=Ampeg: The Story Behind the Sound|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O36Ro9MSkccC&pg=RA1-PA281|accessdate=19 November 2013|year=1999|publisher=Hal Leonard|isbn=9780793579518|page=281}}</ref> Typically, the pentode was used for the input stage, and the triode as a [[Phase inversion|phase inverter]].<ref name="Linde1995">{{cite book|last=Linde|first=Rainer Zur|title=Build Your Own AF Valve Amplifiers: Circuits for Hi-fi and Musical Instruments|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dPTb1Djl1bgC&pg=PA18|accessdate=19 November 2013|year=1995|publisher=Elektor International Media|isbn=9780905705392|page=18}}</ref> The tube was used in a number of American guitar amplifiers; the [[Gibson Guitar Corporation]], for instance, used the 7199 in 1961's [[Gibson Falcon|Falcon]] for the reverb circuit.<ref name="hunter">{{cite news|title=The Gibson GA-19RVT|last=Hunter|first=Dave|date=May 2012|work=[[Vintage Guitar (magazine)|Vintage Guitar]]|pages=62–64}}</ref> [[Ampeg]] also used the 7199 extensively.<ref name="HopkinsMoore1999"/> Notable is the Dynaco ST-70 stereo amplifier introduced in 1959 which used a 7199 tube in the driver section of each channel. Over the next decade more than 350,000 of these amplifiers were produced.<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynaco</ref> American 7199 production ended sometime in the 1980s while the Soviet tube company Sovtek produced one until roughly 2007. As a result the tube is becoming increasingly scarce. Another tube of the same type found in far more plentiful supply is the [[6U8A]], which is electrically identical, but with a different pinout configuration. The 6U8A can be substituted for a 7199 with a slight modification to the wiring of its tube socket.<ref>https://www.tubedepot.com/t/tubes/preamp-tubes/7199</ref>
