'''Staggered fermion''' is a technical subtlety that arises when [[fermion]]ic fields are included in [[lattice gauge theory]]. When one does so, many new unphysical fermionic excitations corresponding to alternating fermionic fields occur in the spectrum. This is known as the [[fermion doubling problem]]. A particular way to resolve this problem, first proposed by [[Leonard Susskind]] and [[John Kogut]] ( [[Kogut-Susskind fermion]]), is the staggered fermion approach where a new [[nonlocal Lagrangian|nonlocal action]] is constructed where the [[Dirac operator]] is treated as a square root.


